* Arthur Koestler - DARKNESS AT NOON (Bantam, 1968).  Translated by Daphne Hardy.  224 pages.  PDF


Originally published in 1940, Arthur Koestler's modern masterpiece is a powerful and haunting portrait of a Communist revolutionary caught in the vicious fray of the Moscow show trials of the late 1930s.  The Modern Library ranked the novel at number eight on its list of the 100 best English-language novels of the 20th century.

During Stalin's purges, Nicholas Rubashov, an aging revolutionary, is imprisoned and psychologically tortured by the party to which he has devoted his life.  Under mounting pressure to confess to crimes he did not commit, Rubashov relives a career that embodies the ironies and betrayals of a revolutionary dictatorship that believes it is an instrument of liberation.

A seminal work of twentieth-century literature, DARKNESS AT NOON powerfully expresses Koestler's disillusionment with the Soviet Union and offers a penetrating exploration of the moral danger inherent in a system that is willing to enforce its beliefs by any means necessary.

This PDF is an improved and smaller version of an older scan in which the page images have been completely reprocessed with contents in bookmarks and accurate pagination.

